  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Edmund Quincy is anxious for news. He heard from Charles Wade, &quot;the reformed drunkard,&quot; that Mrs. Abigail Folsom has left Boston for another city. He hopes that the proceeds of the anti-slavery fair will be enough to pay off the debts of the Massachusetts Anti-Slavery Society. He refers to the ball to be given in honor of the Prince de Joinville. He recalls a remark by Talleyrand about American luxury, which was made in the presence of George Ticknor, who repeated it to Edmund Quincy.</subfield>
